    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Originalists ground their argument in historical evidence, asserting that the Founders understood the right to keep and bear arms in a specific, limited context. They analyze founding-era documents and state constitutions to define the scope of the amendment at the time it was ratified. Conversely, critics label this \"activism\" when they believe the Court is imposing contemporary social values onto historical texts, thus creating new rights or restraints not contemplated by the original framers. The flaw in originalism often cited is that it struggles to account for how societal understanding of rights evolves over centuries.",
      "source": "target",
